WeRateDogs Analysis¶

They're statistically significant breeds, Brent¶

Author: Ken Norton (ken@kennethnorton.com)

The WeRateDogs Twitter account (@dog_rates) has a simple premise: they take photos of peoples' dogs and rate them on a 1-10 scale, often rating dogs well above 10. Since its inception in 2015, the account has grown to more than 8 million followers.

WeRateDogs went mainstream – and launched a meme – during a notorious exchange in 2016, when, as described by Know Your Meme, "Twitter user @brant took issue with the account's rating system, tweeting @dog_rates to tell them it didn't make any sense. @dog_rates replied with 'they're good dogs Brent,' purposefully misspelling @brant's name."

WeRateDogs was right, they are good dogs. But are some breeds of dog more good than others? We set out to answer that question and put our top data analyst on the task.

First, we downloaded a complete archive of the @dog_rates Twitter history. Then, we sent all of the images through a neural network that classified dogs by their breeds. The top breeds rated by @dog_rates are:

Breed # of Tweets
Golden Retriever 116
Pembroke (Welsh Corgi) 70
Labrador Retriever 63
Chihuahua 47
Pug 43
Samoyed 29
Pomeranian 29
Chow 26
Toy Poodle 24
French Bulldog 21

When we examined WeRateDogs' unique rating system, we didn't find any statistically significant difference in how dogs were rated. It seems WeRateDogs likes all dogs equally.

But what about WeRateDogs' followers? They they like certain breeds more than others? To answer that question, we looked at favorites ("likes") and retweets. Here are the top ten breeds when it comes to who other users favorite and retweet:

Breed Average # of Faves + RTs
French Bulldog 23,265
Labrador Retriever 17,375
Samoyed 16,704
Pembroke (Welsh Corgi) 15,973
Golden Retriever 15,496
Cocker Spaniel 15,097
Chow 14,217
Malamute 13,504
German Shepherd 12,283
Chihuahua 12,274

The French Bulldogs appears to be most popular with followers, despite being only the 10th most popular breed shared. Our data analyst crunched the numbers and confirmed it: French Bulldogs, along with Pembrokes, Labrador Retrievers, Samoyeds, and Golden Retrievers are statistically more likely to receive more likes and retweets than other breeds.

Now we know!
